The JavaScript this Keyword:

#) What is this?
    - 💡When the this keyword is used in a function, it refers to an Object.
    - 💡Which Object, is not decided when the function is written.
    - 💡The value of this is decided when the function is called.
    - see this.html from chapter 10. JS Objects
    - ⚠️Make sure you understand basic JavaScript functions before continuing.


#) Functions are Object Methods:
    - 💡All JavaScript functions are object methods.
    - 💡A function can be:
        👉 A method of a JavaScript object
        👉 A method of the global object


1️⃣ this in an Object Method:
    - When a function is an object method:
    - 💡this refers to the object that owns the method.

            const person = {
                firstName: "John",
                lastName: "Doe",
                fullName: function() {
                    return this.firstName + " " + this.lastName;
                }
            };
            person.fullName();
        
        -> 💡In the example above, this refers to the person object.
        -> this.firstName means the firstName property of person.
        -> 💡this.firstName is the same as person.firstName.


2️⃣ this in a Function (Default):
    - By default, when this is used in a regular function, this refers to the global object.

            function myFunction() {
                return this;
            }
            document.getElementById("1").innerHTML = `this is = ${myFunction()}`; // [object Window]

        -> ⚠️In the example above, this is the global object.


3️⃣ this in a Function (Strict Mode):
    - JavaScript strict mode does not allow default binding.
    - ⚠️In strict mode, this used inside a function is undefined.

            "use strict";
            function myFunction() {
                return this;
            }
            document.getElementById("1").innerHTML = `this is = ${myFunction()}`;   // undefined
        
        -> In the example above, this is undefined.


4️⃣ this Alone:
    - When used outside a function, this always refers to the global object.
    - In a browser window the global object is [object Window]:

            let x = this;
            document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = "This is: " + x;    // [object Window]

    - ⚠️⚠️In strict mode, when used outside a function, this also refers to the global object:

            "use strict";
            let x = this;
            document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = "This is: " + x;    // [object Window]
    
    - In both the examples above, this is the global object. It is so because , 💡this is in the global
        scope.


5️⃣ JavaScript globalThis:
    - In JavaScript, globalThis is a special built-in object that provides a standard way to access the
        global object, regardless of the environment your code runs in - whether it is a browser,
        Node.js, a Web Worker, or another JS runtime.
    - 💡The global object is the top-level object in a JavaScript environment:
        👉 In browsers, it is window.
        👉 In Node.js, it is global.
        👉 In Web Workers, it is self.
    
    - ⚠️Each environment used to have its own name for this object. This caused compatibility issues for
        code meant to run everywhere.
    - 💡globalThis was introduced in ECMAScript 2020 (ES11) to solve that problem. It is a unified
        reference to the global object, no matter the environment.

            globalThis === window; // true in browsers
            globalThis === global; // true in Node.js


6️⃣ this in Event Handlers:
    - 💡In HTML event handlers, this refers to the HTML element that received the event:

            <button onclick="this.innerHTML='I was Clicked!'">Click Me!</button>
            or,
            <button onclick="this.style.display='none'">Click to Remove Me!</button>


7️⃣ this in Arrow Functions:
    - Arrow functions do not have their own this. They inherit this from the surrounding scope.
    - In regular functions the this keyword represents the object that called the function, which could
        be the window, the document, a button or whatever.
    - 💡With arrow functions the this keyword always represents the object that defined the arrow
        function.
    - see thisArrowFn.html


#) This Precedence:
    - Use the following precedence of order to determine which object this refers to:

        Order	Object	        Because
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
        1	    bind()	        this is in a function being called using bind()
        2	    apply()	        this is in a function being called using apply()
        2	    call()	        this is in a function being called using call()
        3	    Object method	this is in an object function (method)
        4	    Global scope	this is in a function in the global scope


#) Examples:
    - Below are two examples that call the same method twice:

    1️⃣ With a regular function: returns two different objects (window and button)
        
        <button id="btn">Click Me!</button>
        <p id="demo"></p>

        <script>
            // Regular function:
            const hello = function() {
                document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML += "<br>This is: " + this;
            }

            //The window object calls the function:
            window.addEventListener("load", hello);

            //A button object calls the function:
            document.getElementById("btn").addEventListener("click", hello);
        </script>

    2️⃣ With an arrow function this represents the owner of the function: returns the window object twice,
        because the window object is the "owner" of the function.

        <button id="btn">Click Me!</button>
        <p id="demo"></p>

        <script>
            // Arrow function
            const hello = () => {
                document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML += "<br>This is: " + this;
            }

            //The window object calls the function:
            window.addEventListener("load", hello);

            //A button object calls the function:
            document.getElementById("btn").addEventListener("click", hello);
        </script>


#) Arrow Functions in Methods:
    - 💡With arrow functions there are no binding of this.
    - 💡They are not well suited for defining object methods.

        <p id="demo"></p>
        <script>
            // Create an object:
            const person = {
                firstName: "John",
                // Arrow function as a method
                sayHello : () => {
                    return this.firstName;
                }
            };

            // Display sayHello:
            document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = person.sayHello();  // undefined
        </script>
    
    - ⚠️The example above does not work as expected because thisdoes not refer to the person object.

    - 💡💡Arrow functions can be useful inside methods when you want to keep the same this value.

        const person = {
            firstName: "John",
            sayHello: function() {
                return () => this.firstName;
            }
        };

        document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = person.sayHello()();  // John

        ⚠️⚠️ see arrowFn.html for clarity in above code specially person.sayHello()(); part